description:
src/lib.rs:72 — `let parts: Vec<&str> = parsed.path().splitn(3, '/').collect();` allocates a Vec just to read three positional items. Idiomatic alternatives:

    // Option A: iterator chain, no allocation
    let mut iter = parsed.path().splitn(3, '/');
    let project = iter.next().filter(|s| !s.is_empty());
    let config = iter.next().filter(|s| !s.is_empty());
    let name = iter.next().filter(|s| !s.is_empty());
    let (project, config, name) = match (project, config, name) {
        (Some(p), Some(c), Some(n)) => (p, c, n),
        _ => return Err(SecretError::InvalidUri("...".into())),
    };

    // Option B: array destructure (Rust 1.81+)
    let [project, config, name] = parsed.path().splitn(3, '/').collect::<Vec<_>>().try_into().ok()
        .filter(|[p, c, n]: &[&str; 3]| !p.is_empty() && !c.is_empty() && !n.is_empty())
        .ok_or_else(|| SecretError::InvalidUri(...))?;

Option A reads better, allocates nothing, and shifts the empty-segment validation to one place. Why it matters: avoids one heap allocation per from_uri call and removes a Vec-then-index pattern that clippy classes as needless_collect-adjacent.
